---
const painPoints = [
  {
    icon: '📄',
    title: '300-page PDFs processed by hand',
    description: 'Ops teams spend hours every morning splitting, reading, and re-keying data from supplier document bundles into spreadsheets before it touches the TMS.',
  },
  {
    icon: '⏱️',
    title: 'Quotes that take hours, not minutes',
    description: 'Rate lookups, margin calculations, and quote formatting are manual and repetitive. Every slow response is a deal lost to a faster competitor.',
  },
  {
    icon: '🔗',
    title: 'Systems that don\'t talk to each other',
    description: 'Data sits in CargoWise, carrier portals, email inboxes, and spreadsheets. Without AI for CargoWise and your other systems, moving data between them is a full-time job for multiple people.',
  },
  {
    icon: '🧑‍💻',
    title: 'New suppliers = engineering effort',
    description: 'Every new supplier means new document formats, new mappings, new edge cases. Onboarding a supplier shouldn\'t require a developer.',
  },
];
---

<section class="section" style="background: linear-gradient(180deg, #FFFFFF 0%, #F8FAFC 100%);">
  <div class="container">
    <!-- Visual: Manual ops chaos image -->
    <div class="mb-12 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-line/70 shadow-lg" data-reveal>
      <img src="/images/section-manual-ops.webp" alt="Manual freight document processing — invoices, airway bills, and packing lists scattered across a desk" class="w-full h-auto" loading="lazy" />
    </div>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-start">
      <!-- Left: Header -->
      <div data-reveal>
        <p class="eyebrow mb-4">
          <span class="eyebrow-dot bg-accent"></span>
          The Problem
        </p>
        <h2 class="section-heading">
          Why Freight Forwarding Operations Still Run on Manual Work
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-ink-3 leading-relaxed">
          Freight forwarding runs on documents, data entry, and manual coordination.
          Most "automation" in logistics is just a dashboard on top of the same broken process.
          The real problem isn't visibility — it's that humans are still the glue between your TMS, carrier portals, and supplier documents. <strong>AI logistics automation</strong> eliminates these manual handoffs entirely — whether you're running CargoWise, SAP TM, or Oracle TMS.
        </p>
        <a href="/solutions" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 mt-8 text-sm font-semibold text-brand hover:gap-3 transition-all duration-200">
          See how we solve this
          <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3" />
          </svg>
        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- Right: Pain point cards -->
      <div class="grid gap-4">
        {painPoints.map((point, i) => (
          <div class="flex gap-4 p-5 rounded-2xl border border-line/70 bg-white hover:shadow-md transition-all duration-200"
               data-reveal data-reveal-delay={String(i + 1)}>
            <span class="text-2xl flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5" aria-hidden="true">{point.icon}</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-ink mb-1">{point.title}</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-ink-3 leading-relaxed">{point.description}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
